P. 58(b)(3). The court finds the Defendant is able to understand these rights as they were reviewed. The Government is not seeking that defendant be detained. The Government and Defendant agree on certain conditions of release. Defendant signed an unsecured bond in the amount of $4,500. Defendant shall be release upon completion of U.S.M.S. processing. Enter Order Setting Conditions of Release and Appearance Bond. Defendant was advised of her rights pursuant to Fed. R. Crim. P. 7(b), and "waives prosecution by indictment." Defendant tendered a signed waiver of an indictment form to the Court. Defendant acknowledged receipt of the information and enters a plea of guilty to count(s) (1) one in the Information. Defendant waives right to trial before District Judge and consents to trial before a U.S. Magistrate Judge. Enter Consent to Proceed Before United States Magistrate Judge in a Misdemeanor Case. The court finds the Defendant is competent and accepts the plea of guilty. Sentencing set for 1/8/20 at 10:00 a.m. Case referred to Probation Office for a pre-sentence investigation. Pre-sentence report filed by 12/4/19. Objections to the pre-sentence report shall be filed by 12/11/19. Response shall be filed by 12/18/19. The Probation Office is directed to release the sentencing recommendation to the parties. Arraignment set for 10/16/19 is stricken. Signed by the Honorable M. David Weisman on October 16, 2019. Mailed notice (ph, ) (Entered: 10/17/2019)

AMENDED JUDGMENT IN A CRIMINAL CASE (Modification of Restitution Order) as to Andrew Owimrin (2) Count(s) 1, 2, Dismissed; Found guilty to Count(s) 1s, 2s, IMPRISONMENT: 52 months on each count to run concurrently. SUPERVISED RELEASE: three years on each count to run concurrently. The court makes the following recommendations to the Bureau of Prisons That defendant be admitted to the Residential Drug Abuse Program (RDAP) if he is otherwise eligible. of That defendant be incarcerated in the northeast region to facilitate visits with his family in New Jersey who live in New Jersey. The defendant shall surrender for service of sentence at the institution designated by the Bureau of Prisons before 2pm on 4/30/2019. *The defendant shall pay restitution in the amount of $557,991.00 in monthly payments of 20% of his gross income. Payments shall begin 30 days after release from prison. The defendant shall pay all outstanding taxes owed or arrange a payment plan with the Internal Revenue Service. During the term of imprisonment, the defendant shall remit restitution in conjunction with the Inmate Financial Responsibility Program, but in any event not less than $25 per quarter. ORDER of USCA (certified copy) as to Thomas Cunningham regarding notice of appeal 117 : Following a jury trial, Thomas Cunningham was found guilty of one count of bank robbery, see 18 U.S.C. 2113(a), and sentenced to 180 months imprisonment, 30 months below his guidelines range of 210 to 240 months. Cunningham appeals, but his appointed counsel has concluded that the appeal is frivolous and moves to withdraw under Anders vs. California, 386 U.S. 738(1967). We review only the issues presented in counsel's facially adequate brief and in Cunningham's response. See Cir. R. 51(b); United States vs. Schuh, 289 F. 3d 968, 973-74 (7th Cir. 2002). Cunningham argues that his sentence was unreasonable. But, as counsel recognizes, the court gave careful consideration to the 18 U.S.C. 3553(a) sentencing factors and believing the guidelines overstated Cunningham's criminal history--imposed a below-guidelnes sentence, so any challenge to the reasonable of the sentence would be frivolous. See United States vs. Chess, 610 F. 3d 965, 967 (7th Cir. 2010). We grant counsel's motion to withdraw and dismiss the appeal. (yap, ) (Entered: 10/01/2010)

Minute Entry for proceedings held 10/13/2016 before Hon. Richard J. Arcara as to Deft, Fredy Vasquez-Morales (1), Count(s) (Information). Waiver of Indictment, Plea and Sentencing is held. Deft waives Indictment and pleads guilty to a one-count Information. Sentencing follows. The Court accepts the terms and conditions of the plea agreement and the plea of guilty. The Presentence Investigation Report is placed in the record under seal. If an appeal is filed, counsel on appeal will be permitted access to the sealed report, except that counsel on appeal will not be permitted access to the recommendation section. Deft is committed to the custody of the Bureau of Prisons for a term of time served; the cost of incarceration fee is waived. Upon release from imprisonment, Deft shall be placed on supervised release for a term of 1 year with standard and special conditions. Deft is to be delivered to a duly authorized Immigration Official for deportation proceedings pursuant to Title 18 U.S.C. Section 3583(d). The Deft shall not re-enter or attempt to re-enter the United States without the written authorization of the Secretary of Homeland Security. Re-entry into the United States without approval of the Secretary of Homeland Security constitutes new criminal conduct which may subject the Deft to criminal prosecution. The Court grant's the Govt's oral motion to dismiss Complaint No. 16-mj-117 as to this Deft. The defendant shall forfeit the defendant's interest in the following property to the United States: $1,151,665.76 in United States currency. ORDER of USCA (certified copy) as to Aran A Carrillo regarding notice of appeal 64 : Aran Carrillo pleaded guilty to conspiring to possess with intent to distribute heroin, 21 U.S.C. 846, 841(a)(1). The District Court sentenced him to 120 months' imprisonment, the statutory minimum given that the conspiracy involved 15 kilograms, see id. 841(b)(1)(A)(1). On appeal Carrillo challenges the district court's decision not to apply the "safety valve", which would have allowed a sentence below the mandatory minimum see 18 U.S.C. 3553(f); U.S.S.G. 5C1.2(a). His sole argument is that the district court committed clear error by finding that he failed to show that he truthfully provided all relevant information to the government. Because the district court committed no such error, we affirm the judgment. (yap, ) (Entered: 05/22/2012)

JUDGMENT as to Alfredo Rodriguez (10), Count(s) 1, Imprisonment: 60 months. Supervised Release: 4 years; Count(s) 2, Dismissed. The court n1akes the following recommendations to the Bureau of Prisons: That the defendant be designated to either the Allenwood Facility or the Danbury Facility or to a facility as close as possible to the Metropolitan New York area that has programs for electricians or welders. The Court also recommends that the defendant be permitted to participate in the RDAP Program. The defendant is remanded to the custody of the United States Marshal. 1. The defendant will participate in an outpatient treatment program approved by the United States Probation Office, which program may include testing to determine whether the defendant has reverted to using drugs or alcohol. The defendant must contribute to the cost of services rendered based on ability to pay and the availability of third-party payments. The Court authorizes the release of available drug treatment evaluations and reports, including the presentence investigation report, to the substance abuse treatment provider. 2. The defendant must submit his person, residence, place of business, vehicle, and any property or electronic devices under his control to a search on the basis that the probation officer has reasonable suspicion that contraband or evidence of a violation of the conditions of your probation/supervised release may be found. The search must be conducted at a reasonable time and in a reasonable manner. Failure to submit to a search may be grounds for revocation. The defendant must inform any other residents that the premises may be subject to search pursuant to this condition. The defendant is to report to the nearest Probation Office within 72 hours of release from custody. The defendant shall be supervised by the district of residence. Lump sum payment of $100.00 due immediately, balance due. (Signed by Judge Loretta A. Preska on 5/24/2018)(ft) Modified on 6/1/2018 (ft). (Entered: 06/01/2018)

The parties shall file simultaneous sentencing briefs by 7/24/2018. In its brief, the Government shall (among any other matters it wishes to address) set forth the specific supervised release conditions it proposes and the justification for imposing each such condition. The parties shall file simultaneous sentencing response briefs by 8/7/2018. In his response brief, Defendant shall (among any other matters he wishes to address) address each supervised release condition proposed by the Probation Office and the Government, stating which conditions he does not oppose and setting forth specific reasons why the other conditions should not be imposed. Pursuant to 18 U.S.C. ยง 3664(d)(1), if restitution is being sought in this case, 60 days prior to the sentencing date, the Government shall provide the Probation Office and the courtroom deputy an electronic standardized spreadsheet (available on the Court's website) with a list of victims and their full current contact information. This list shall include any amounts subject to restitution. If the Government is not able to provide the full victim list 60 days prior to sentencing, they shall file a motion to request an extension of time to compile the information, to the extent permitted by 18 U.S.C. ยง 3664(d)(5). Signed by the Honorable Gary Feinerman on 4/16/2018. Mailed notice. (ew, ) (Entered: 04/17/2018)

Defense Counsel John P. Furman, Esquire (appointed). Government Counsel Assistant U. S. Attorney Lawrence Bullard standing in for Assistant U. S. Attorney Christopher Baugh. Defendant's guilty plea was accepted on 2/24/2017 and Defendant was found guilty as charged. The plea agreement was written. The maximum penalties are 10 years imprisonment, $250,000.00 fine, SRT 3 years, SA $100.00, any restitution the Court finds is appropriate. Defendant advised of enhancement penalty of the statute: if subject to 18:924(e), then minimum, mandatory penalty is 15 years up to life imprisonment, and 5 years SRT. Sentencing set for 6/5/2017 at 10:30 AM in US Courthouse, Courtroom 2B, 113 St. Joseph Street, Mobile, AL 36602 before Senior Judge Callie V. S. Granade. Presentence Investigation Report due 5/1/2017. On or before 5/22/2017 the parties shall each file a Position with Respect to Sentencing Factors in accordance with Criminal Local Rule 32(B)(4). JUDGMENT as to Ruben Israel Hernandez-Correa (1), Count(s) 1, Pursuant to the Sentencing Reform Act of 1984, as amended, it is the judgment of the Court that the defendant, RUBEN ISRAEL HERNANDEZ-CORREA, is hereby committed to the custody of the Federal Bureau of Prisons for a period of EIGHTEEN (18) months imprisonment. The Court does not order a fine because the defendant does not have the financial resources or future earning capacity to pay a fine. It is further ordered that the defendant pay a special assessment of $100. It is ordered that upon release from imprisonment the defendant shall be placed on supervised release for a term of ONE (1) year. As a condition of supervised release, upon the completion of the sentence of imprisonment, the defendant shall be surrendered to a duly-authorized immigration official for deportation in accordance with the established procedures provided by the Immigration and Nationality Act, 8 U.S.C. 1101 et seq. As a further condition of supervised release, if ordered deported or removed, the defendant shall remain outside the United States. The Court recommends to the BOP that the defendant be housed at an FCI facility within the Northern District of Texas area, if possible. The defendant is remanded to the custody of the US Marshal (Ordered by Judge Reed C. O'Connor on 12/26/2017) (ewd) (Entered: 12/26/2017)

JUDGMENT as to Michael Brandon Mann (1), Count(s) 1, Dismissed on motion of the defendant.; Count(s) 2, The defendant is hereby committed to the custody of the Federal Bureau of Prisons to be imprisoned for a total term of TWENTY FOUR (24) months. The defendant shall pay the mandatory $100.00 special assessment fee, $1,000.00 in restitution, and $5,000.00 JVTA, all due beginning immediately. The court makes the following recommendations to the Bureau of Prisons: The defendant be designated to a Bureau of Prison closest to his home in South Carolina. The defendant shall surrender for service of sentence at the institution designated by the Bureau of Prisons: as notified by the United States Marshal. Upon release from imprisonment, the defendant shall be on supervised release for a term of LIFE. While on supervised release, the defendant shall comply with the mandatory and standard conditions of supervision outlined in 18 USC ยง 3583(d). The defendant shall also comply with the following special conditions for the reasons set forth in the presentence report which has previously been adopted by the Court as the finding of facts for the purposes of sentencing: 1. The defendant shall pay any remaining restitution in the amount of $1,000 at a rate of no less than $20 per month, beginning within 60 days of release. The payments shall be made payable to Clerk, U.S. District Court and mailed to PO Box 835, Charleston, SC 29402. Interest on any restitution ordered as to this defendant is waived. Payments shall be adjusted accordingly, based upon the defendants ability to pay as determined by the Court. 2. Once restitution and the special assessment have been satisfied, the defendant shall pay the remaining JVTA in the amount of $5,000 at a rate of no less than $20.00 per month. Interest on any JVTA ordered as to this defendant is waived. Payments shall be adjusted accordingly, based upon the defendants ability to pay as determined by the Court. 3.The defendant shall participate in a program of mental health counseling and/or treatment as deemed necessary by the U.S. Probation Officer, until such time as the defendants release from the program is approved by the U.S. Probation Officer. 4.The defendant shall participate in the Computer/Internet Monitoring Program and abide by the rules of that program, as approved by the U.S. Probation Officer. 5. The defendant shall participate in a sex offender treatment program, approved by the U.S. Probation Office, which may include physiological and psychological testing. 6. The defendant shall contribute to the costs of any treatment, drug testing and/or location monitoring not to exceed an amount determined reasonable by the court approved U.S. Probation Office's Sliding Scale for Services, and shall cooperate in securing any applicable third-party payment, such as insurance or Medicaid. 7. The defendant shall not possess, procure, purchase or otherwise obtain access to any form of computer network, bulletin board, Internet, or exchange format involving computers unless specifically approved by the United States Probation Office. 8. The defendant shall have no unsupervised contact with children under the age 18, without approval and consent of the United States Probation Officer. 9. The defendant shall comply with any sex offender registration laws in accordance with the Sex Offender Registration and Notification Act (SORNA), including any applicable state laws. 10. The defendant shall not possess any audio or visual depictions containing sexually explicit conduct as defined in 18 U.S.C. ยง 2256(2)(A). 11. The defendant shall not frequent adult book stores, sex shops, topless bars, or locations that act as a sexual stimulus.. 12. The defendant shall submit to random polygraphs for treatment purposes, as well as compliance to the standard conditions of supervision, to be conducted by any person deemed appropriate by the United States Probation Officer as a treatment tool to be used in conjunction with sex offender treatment program with the following limitations:(A) Answers to questions asked during a polygraph test cannot be used against the defendant in any criminal proceeding other than an action to extend, modify, or revoke supervised release. (B) Information obtained during polygraph testing cannot be made public or released to state or any other prosecuting authorities; and (C) Information obtained during polygraph testing cannot be used in a civil commitment proceeding under state or federal law. The defendant shall make co-payments up to the total costs of the polygraph. These payments shall be made in addition to co-payments made for sex offender treatment and shall be based on the sliding scale. You must make restitution in accordance with 18 U.S.C. ยงยง 3663 and 3663A or any other statute authorizing a sentence of restitution. You must cooperate in the collection of DNA as directed by the probation officer. You must comply with the requirements of the Sex Offender Registration and Notification Act (42 U.S.C. ยง16901, et seq.) as directed by the probation officer, the Bureau of Prisons, or any state sex offender registration agency in the location where you reside, work, are a student, or were convicted of a qualifying offense. Consent to Rule 11 Plea In a Felony Case Before United States Magistrate signatures verified and filed. Waiver of Indictment signatures verified and filed. Memorandum of Plea Agreement signatures verified and filed. Defendant advised of his rights. Court informs Defendant of sentencing guidelines, possible departure from sentencing guidelines, supervised release, etc. Plea of Guilty to the Information entered by the Defendant. Court accepts the guilty plea, and the defendant is adjudged guilty. R&R signed, with 14 days to object. Pre-Sentence report ordered from USPO. SENTENCING as to the Information set for 1/18/18 @ 1:30 p.m. HG. Bail Hearing as to Omri Shapira held on 10/4/2017. Defendant and Government concur with the Pretrial Services recommendation. The Court taking judicial notice of the documents on file, the USPTS' report, and the comments of counsel, adopts the recommendation of Pretrial Services and modifies the terms and conditions of bail: The following conditions are deleted: (7h3) Travel is restricted to: the island of Oahu.; (7p3) Comply with the Location Monitoring program under the direction of Pretrial Services. The Court authorizes release under the CURFEW restriction. Unless otherwise ordered in Special Condition (7o), you are restricted to your residence during the curfew hours as determined by Pretrial Services. Placement under a curfew restriction enables the defendant to move freely within the Mahoney Hale facility. All requests to leave the facility must be approved in advance and the defendant's movements outside of Mahoney Hale are subject to GPS tracking and monitoring.; (7q) Placement at MAHONEY HALE. You are restricted to the facility at all times except as pre-approved by Pretrial Services. You are required to abide by all established rules of the facility.; (7t2) Do not consume any alcoholic beverages or products containing alcohol while at the halfway house/treatment program, as prohibited by program rules.; (7u1) Do not use or possess illicit drugs, and do not be in the presence of illicit drug use or drug users/traffickers.; (7v1) To ensure compliance with the restriction on illicit drug use, submit to random drug detection testing as approved by Pretrial Services. Do not obstruct, attempt to obstruct, or tamper with the drug detection testing process in any manner.; (7v1) To ensure compliance with the restriction on illicit drug use, submit to random drug detection testing as approved by Pretrial Services. Do not obstruct, attempt to obstruct, or tamper with the drug detection testing process in any manner.; Release is delayed pending the posting of the passport. The following conditions are added: (7h3) Travel is restricted to: the islands of Maui and Oahu for Court and Immigration purposes.; (7p3) Comply with the Location Monitoring program under the direction of Pretrial Services. The Court authorizes release under the CURFEW restriction. Unless otherwise ordered in Special Condition (7o), you are restricted to your residence during the curfew hours as determined by Pretrial Services.; OTHER: Release from Mahoney Hale is delayed until travel arrangements are verified.; OTHER: Pretrial Services is authorized to conduct the initial home installation on a delayed basis.; All other terms and conditions remain in full force and effect. The defendant is sentenced to thirty(30) years on count three (3s) to run concurrent with thirty(30)years on counts five(5s),six(6s)and seven(7s), consecutive with thirty(30)years on count four(4s), which will run concurrent to twenty(20)years on count eight(8s) consecutive with thirty(30)years for count one(1s), which will run concurrent with thirty(30)years on count two (2s) and consecutive to ten(10)years for count nine(9s). Upon release from imprisonment the defendant shall be on supervised release for the periods specified for each count of conviction. The defendant is sentenced on all count(s) of conviction, namely, count one(1s)-seven(7s) to a period of five(5)years each of supervised release. Counts eight(8s) and nine (9s), three years each, said periods to run concurrent to count one(s)-seven(7s). Mandatory conditions of supervised release. Standard conditions of supervised release.The remaining counts are dismissed. Schedule of payments. The defendant is immediately remanded to the custody of the United States Marshal. Charles Burt terminated. Signed by Judge Wayne R. Andersen on 9/5/06.Mailed notice (pmp, ) (Entered: 09/06/2006)
